<subSubSection id="C33E48FCE115FF91C9C53798E19AFEFD" pageId="3" pageNumber="269" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9B1B77E115FF91C9C53798E19AFEFD" blockId="3.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="269">
<emphasis id="B950C765E115FF91C9C53798E074FF50" bold="true" box="[199,315,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="269">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C2460F4E115FF91CB933796E282FF50" authority="Dworakowska" authorityName="Dworakowska" box="[657,973,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hepneriana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="269" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="joannae">
<emphasis id="B950C765E115FF91CB933796E242FF4F" box="[657,781,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="269">H. joannae</emphasis>
(Dworakowska)
</taxonomicName>
, but its aedeagal shaft is broader, and the aedeagal subapical processes are broader, longer and serrated on the outer margin. 
<emphasis id="B950C765E115FF91C9C537D0E001FF18" bold="true" box="[199,334,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="269">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis id="B950C765E115FF91CA8C37EFE545FF18" box="[910,1034,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="269">applanatus</emphasis>
”, referring to the flattened aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
